b'' b'reposted by request these images are great, but they are also large' b'(1500x1500 pixels is a typical size). be warned.' b'' b'regards, tom lane' b'' b'-------------' b'newsgroups: comp.archives' b'date: feb gmt' b'x-original-newsgroups: rec.arts.books' b'x-original-date: feb gmt' b'' b'archive-name: auto/rec.arts.books/vatican-library-exhibit-at-library-of-congress-online' b'' b'' b'this is from another newsgroup; looks quite interesting...' b'rms' b'' b'' b'announcing' b'a new' b'online exhibit' b'from' b'the library of congress' b'' b'' b'' b'rome reborn: the vatican library renaissance culture' b'' b'an exhibit at the' b'library of congress' b'washington, dc b'' b'available by anonymous ftp from' b'seq1.loc.gov' b'(140.147.3.12)' b'' b'/pub/vatican.exhibit' b'' b'' b'' b'rome reborn: the vatican library and renaissance culture' b"presents some of the vatican library's most precious" b'manuscripts, books, and maps--many of which played a key role in' b'the humanist recovery of the classical heritage of greece and' b'rome. the exhibition presents the untold story of the vatican' b'library as the intellectual driving force behind the emergence of' b'rome as a political and scholarly superpower during the' b'renaissance. the exhibit will be on display in the jefferson' b'building of the library of congress from january through' b'april the online exhibit will be available by' b'anonymous ftp indefinitely.' b'' b'the exhibit is divided into nine sections: the vatican' b'library, archaeology, humanism, mathematics, music, medicine b'biology, nature described, a wider world i: how the orient came' b'to rome, and a wider world ii: how rome went to china. each' b'section consists of its own sub-directory within the /exhibit' b'directory and contains the exhibit text for that section and' b'separate jpeg image files for each object. this online exhibit' b'includes not only objects from the library of congress exhibit,' b'but also the alternate objects (brought from rome to be used if' b'there were a problem with one of the primary objects) and items' b'omitted later in the planning process.' b'' b'this exhibit will be of interest to medieval and renaissance' b'scholars in particular, but also to art historians, historians of' b'science or medicine, early music scholars, students of the' b'humanist movement, students of printing and the printed word,' b'theologians, scholars of both far and near eastern studies, and' b'to librarians and information professionals. please get the' b'readme file for details on what files this exhibit contains. if' b'you have questions about how to use ftp, speak to your local' b'computer support person. if you have questions or comments about' b'while if you have any questions or comments on the system please' b'contact me.' b'' b'-- k.d. ellis' b'' b'++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++' b'k.d. ellis' b'special projects office' b'library of congress' b'washington, dc 